FIFA - 19 Data - Clustering¶

Data Mining for BI project to analyze and discover insights of the attributes of each player registered in the latest edition of FIFA 19 database using clustering techiques.

Data¶

Detailed attributes for every player registered in the latest edition of FIFA 19 database:

  • Original data from Kaggle ** There are 89 columns and 18207 rows

def getNumericalData(data, quality):
    numData = pd.DataFrame()
    for col in data.columns:
        if str(data[col].dtype) != "object":
            numData[col] = data[col]
    if quality and len(numData.columns) > 0:
        numData = numData.fillna(numData.mean())
    print(numData.shape)
    return numData;

Insights

There is a large number of correlated variables in the original dataset, which is an ideal scenario to run a PCA and thus reduce the dimensions while maintaining the variance and the direction of the data.

Principal Component Analysis¶

Selecting categorical and numeric variables

Only the numeric variables of the dataset will be used to perform the PCA. Then, the variables that you do not want to include in the analysis are discarded.

In [0]:
# Calculates the K-Means for (x, y) dataset
def runKMeans(k_clusters):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k_clusters, algorithm = "elkan", random_state = 0)
    kmeans = kmeans.fit(train)
    
    # Getting the cluster labels
    clusters = kmeans.predict(train)
    
    # Centroid values
    centroids = kmeans.cluster_centers_
    
    # Plotting K-Means result
    plotKMeansData(train, k_clusters, centroids, clusters)
In [0]:
# Create scatter plot with K-Means data
def plotKMeansData(data, k_clusters, centroids, clusters):
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize = (14, 14))
    
    # Plotting vars
    colors = ["#1f77b4", "#2ca02c", "#d62728", "#ff7f0e"]
    nData = len(data)
    
    # Create scatter plot
    for i in range(k_clusters):
        points = np.array([data[j] for j in range(nData) if clusters[j] == i])
        sns.scatterplot( ax=ax1,x = points[:, 0], y = points[:, 1], size = 5, color = colors[i],legend = False)
    plt.scatter(centroids[:, 0], centroids[:, 1], s = 20, color = "black", marker = "D")
    
    # Plot setup
    ax1.set_xlabel("PC 1", fontsize = 12)
    ax1.set_ylabel("PC 2", fontsize = 12)
    ax1.set_title("Players by Zones", fontsize = 20)   
    ax1.grid()

In [0]:
def plotHierData(data, h_clusters, clusters):
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize = (14, 14))
    
    # Plotting vars
    colors = ["#1f77b4", "#2ca02c", "#d62728", "#ff7f0e"]
    nData = len(data)
    
    # Create scatter plot
    for i in range(h_clusters):
        points = np.array([data[j] for j in range(nData) if clusters[j] == i])
        sns.scatterplot( ax=ax1,x = points[:, 0], y = points[:, 1], size = 5, color = colors[i],legend = False)
    
    # Plot setup
    ax1.set_xlabel("PC 1", fontsize = 12)
    ax1.set_ylabel("PC 2", fontsize = 12)
    ax1.set_title("Players by Zones", fontsize = 20)   
    ax1.grid()
In [38]:
h_clusters = 4
hiercluster = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4, affinity='euclidean', linkage='ward')  

# Getting the cluster labels
hiercluster = hiercluster.fit_predict(train)

# Plotting H-Means result
plotHierData(train, h_clusters, hiercluster)

Conclusion¶

We can see the clusters formed by using different clustering algorithms - K-means and Hierarchical algorithms respectively .

We can also see the silhouette scores for each.

By Comparing the clusters and the scores, we could say that the hierarchical way of clustering has a significantly better performace than k-means for fifa19 dataset. Thus Hierarchical will be our champion way and k-means will be our challenger.
